
GIT STASHING !!

Sometimes we need to quickly switch tasks or fix a bug, but we're not ready to commit our work.
git stash lets us save our uncommitted changes and return to a clean working directory.
we can come back and restore our changes later.

> Here are some common use cases 
-- Switch branches safely: Save our work before changing branches.
-- Handle emergencies: Stash our work to fix something urgent, then restore it.
-- Keep our work-in-progress safe: Avoid messy commits or losing changes.

> What is a stash stack?
-- Each time we run git stash, our changes are saved on top of a "stack".
   The most recent stash is on top, and we can apply or drop stashes from the top down, or pick a specific one from the list.

>  What is Git Stash Apply ?
-- You can use git switch apply to apply whatever is stashed away, without removing it from stash. 
   This can be useful if you want to apply stashed changes to multiple branches. 

> Commands 
--  To save all the uncommitted changes (staged and unstaged) and stash them
    [ git stash ] / [ git stash save ]
--  To lets us add a descriptive message to our stash so we can remember what we were working on.
    [ git stash push -m "<message>" ]
--  To show all the stashes we have saved so far, with their names and messages.
    [ git stash list ]
--  To show a summary of what files and changes are in our most recent stash.
    [ git stash show ] 
--  To show the exact lines that were changed in our most recent stash.
    [ git stash show -p ]
--  To restore our most recent stashed changes, but keeps the stash in the list so we can use it again if needed.
    [ git stash apply ]
--  To let us restore a specific stash from our list, not just the most recent one.
    [ git stash apply stash@{n} ] -> n denotes numbers like 1 , 2 etc. 
--  To restore our most recent stash and removes it from the list at the same time.
    [ git stash pop ] 
--  To deletes a specific stash from our list when we no longer need it.
    [ git stash drop stash@{n} ] ->  n denotes numbers like 1 , 2 etc. 
--  To delete all our stashes at once. Be careful! This cannot be undone!
    [ git stash clear ] 
--  To creates a new branch and applies our stashed changes to it.
    [ git stash <new_branch_name> stash@{n} ] 




